# Git Learning and Practical Implementation Log

## Introduction

As part of my DevOps internship learning journey, I started exploring Git, a distributed version control system widely used for source code management and collaboration. The objective of this practice session was to understand Git fundamentals, perform hands-on exercises using Git Bash, and learn how Git tracks and manages file changes.

---

## Environment Setup

### Git Installation Verification

The first step was to verify whether Git was installed correctly on the system.

Command executed:

git --version

Observation:

The installed Git version was displayed successfully, confirming that Git was properly configured and ready for use.

Learning:

Git commands can only be executed if Git is correctly installed and available in the system path.

---

## Understanding Git and Git Bash

During the learning process, I explored the difference between Git and Git Bash.

Git:

* A distributed version control system.
* Used to track file changes and maintain project history.

Git Bash:

* A command-line interface for Windows.
* Provides a Linux-like environment for executing Git commands.

Learning:

Git is the actual version control software, whereas Git Bash is a terminal used to interact with Git.

---

## Navigating the File System

To understand the current working location and available files, several Linux commands were practiced.

Commands used:

pwd

ls

ls -a

Purpose:

* pwd displays the current working directory.
* ls lists files and folders.
* ls -a displays all files, including hidden files.

Learning:

These commands are frequently used in DevOps environments for file system navigation.

---

## Creating a Practice Directory

A dedicated practice directory was created to perform Git exercises.

Commands executed:

mkdir practice

cd practice

Purpose:

* Create a new folder named practice.
* Move into the folder for further operations.

Learning:

Maintaining a separate workspace prevents accidental modifications to existing projects.

---

## Repository Initialization

After entering the practice directory, Git was initialized.

Command executed:

git init

Observation:

Git created a hidden .git directory and displayed a successful initialization message.

Learning:

The git init command converts a normal folder into a Git repository.

The .git directory stores:

* Commit history
* Branch information
* Repository configuration
* Git metadata

An important observation was that after initialization, the terminal prompt displayed:

(master)

This indicated that the current folder had become a Git repository and the active branch was master.

---

## Understanding Repository Structure

After initialization, hidden files were displayed using:

ls -a

Observation:

The .git directory became visible.

Learning:

A Git repository consists of project files and a hidden .git directory that acts as the internal database for Git operations.

---

## Creating Files Using Git Bash

Text files were created directly from the terminal.

Commands executed:

echo hello > file1.txt

echo hello > file2.txt

Observation:

Even though the files did not previously exist, Git Bash automatically created them.

Learning:

The > operator creates a file if it does not exist and writes content into it.

---

## Understanding File Redirection Operators

Two file redirection operators were studied.

Overwrite:

echo suzo > file1.txt

Append:

echo suzo >> file1.txt

Learning:

The single greater-than symbol (>) replaces existing file content.

The double greater-than symbol (>>) appends content to the existing file without removing previous data.

This was one of the important observations made during the practice session.

---

## Checking Repository Status

The repository state was monitored using:

git status

Purpose:

To identify:

* Untracked files
* Modified files
* Staged files
* Current branch information

Learning:

git status is one of the most frequently used Git commands because it provides a complete view of repository changes.

---

## Understanding the Staging Area

Files were added to the staging area using:

git add file1.txt

git add file2.txt

Observation:

Git reported the files under:

Changes to be committed

Learning:

Git uses a staging area as an intermediate step before creating a commit.

Workflow observed:

Working Directory
↓
git add
↓
Staging Area
↓
git commit
↓
Repository

---

## Understanding File Modification After Staging

After staging a file, its content was modified again.

Command executed:

echo suzo > file1.txt

Observation:

Git displayed:

Changes to be committed

and

Changes not staged for commit

at the same time.

Learning:

Git was tracking two different versions:

* One version in the staging area.
* Another version in the working directory.

This demonstrated how Git keeps track of file changes separately before committing.

---

## Re-staging Modified Files

The modified file was added again using:

git add file1.txt

Observation:

The unstaged modification warning disappeared.

Learning:

Running git add again updates the staging area with the latest file version.

---

## Understanding Commits

An attempt was made to execute:

git commit -m

Observation:

Git returned an error because no commit message was provided.

Correct command:

git commit -m "Initial commit"

Learning:

A commit message is mandatory when using the -m option.

A commit represents a snapshot of the project at a specific point in time.

---

## Exploring Vim Editor

During commit operations, Git opened the Vim editor.

Observations:

* Vim opened the COMMIT_EDITMSG file.
* Exiting Vim initially caused confusion.

Learning:

Useful Vim commands:

Exit without saving:

:q!

Save and exit:

:wq

This helped in understanding how Git interacts with text editors during commit creation.

---

## Configuring Visual Studio Code as the Default Git Editor

To avoid using Vim, Visual Studio Code was configured as the default Git editor.

Verification:

code --version

Configuration:

git config --global core.editor "code --wait"

Learning:

Git can be integrated with modern editors to simplify commit message editing.

---

## Understanding Git Branches

The concept of branches was explored conceptually.

Learning:

A branch provides an isolated workspace for development.

Benefits:

* Safe experimentation
* Feature development
* Team collaboration
* Reduced risk of affecting the main codebase

The default branch observed during practice was:

master

